We write a simple function to determine the classification error

check_err <- function(arr1, arr2){
  count = 0
  for (i in 1:length(arr1)){
    if (arr1[i] == arr2[i]) {
      count = count + 1
    }
  }
  return (1 - (count/length(arr1)))
}

Part (a)

Design of tree from scratch

I adopt a simplistic approach to creating the tree by determining best split based on highest information gain. Then, using recursion, I will keep creating child nodes. I calculate the information gain based on difference of gini impurity for the parent vis-a-vis the children nodes.

For the tree, I will go to the left node whenever the answer is Yes. For categorical variables, the question is Var = 1?, and for age variable, the question is Var < age_value?

#Function to calculate Gini Impurity
gini_impurity <- function(df) {
  y_arr <- df$voted
  n_arr <- length(y_arr)
  p1 <- sum(y_arr == 1)/n_arr
  p0 <- sum(y_arr == 0)/n_arr
  gini_impurity <- 1 - p1**2 - p0**2
  return(gini_impurity)
}

#Function to calculate Information Gain
info_gain <- function(left, right, parent){
  l_weight <- nrow(left)/nrow(parent)
  r_weight <- nrow(right)/nrow(parent)
  info_gain <- gini_impurity(parent) - l_weight*gini_impurity(left) - r_weight*gini_impurity(right)
  return(info_gain)
}

#Function to create a split.
#Since Age is a continuous variable and all others are categorical, I treat them differently.
create_split <- function(df, col_name, col_value) {
  if (col_name != 'age'){
    left_rows <- which(df[[col_name]] ==  col_value)
    left <- df[left_rows,]
    right <- df[-left_rows,]  
  }
  else{
    left_rows <- which(df[[col_name]] <  col_value)
    left <- df[left_rows,]
    right <- df[-left_rows,]
  }
  return(list(left,right))
}

#Finding split which maximized information gain
find_best_split <- function(df){
  best_gain <- 0
  split_col_name <- NULL
  split_col_value <- NULL
  age_ls <- unique(df$age) #to check on all age values within the sub-dataset
  for (i in 1:8){
    if (coln[i] != 'age'){
      splits <- create_split(df,coln[i],1)
      if (nrow(splits[[1]]) == 0 |nrow(splits[[2]]) == 0){
        next
      }
      else{
        gain <- info_gain(splits[[1]],splits[[2]],df)
        #Update gain and split points only if I can improve gain
        if (gain > best_gain){
          best_gain <- gain
          split_col_value <- 1
          split_col_name <- coln[i]
          min_obs <- min(nrow(splits[[1]]),nrow(splits[[2]]))
        }
      }
    }
    else{
      for (j in 1:length(age_ls)){
        splits <- create_split(df,coln[i],age_ls[j])
        if (nrow(splits[[1]]) == 0 |nrow(splits[[2]]) == 0){
          next
        }
        else{
          gain <- info_gain(splits[[1]],splits[[2]],df)
          if (gain > best_gain){
              best_gain <- gain
              split_col_value <- age_ls[j]
              split_col_name <- coln[i]
              min_obs <- min(nrow(splits[[1]]),nrow(splits[[2]]))
          }
        } 
      }
    }  
  }
  return(c(best_gain,split_col_name,split_col_value))
}

det_criteria <- function(x,y){
  if (y != 'age'){
    if (x%%2 == 1){
      return('Yes')
    }
    else{
      return('No')
    }
  }
  else{
    if (x%%2 == 1){
      return('Less than')
    }
    else{
      return('More or equal')
    }
  }
}

Creating the tree (finally!)

#Initiating a global dataframe to store the results of the tree
output_tree <- data.frame(node_number = integer(), #store the current node
                          split_var = character(), #store the variable on which the tree needs to be split
                          split_value = integer(), #store the value condition at which the tree needs to be split
                          parent = integer(), #store the parent node
                          leaf_log = logical(), #store TRUE if its the terminal node
                          y_val = integer(), # predicted output based on construction tree
                          criteria = character()) # move to current node if criteria is met - only for reading the table
output_tree[1,] <- c(0,NA,NA, -1, FALSE, NA, 'Root')

build_tree <- function(df,curr_node, parent_node, variable, value){
  est_val <- NA
  leaf = FALSE
  
  #Pushing node details into the dataframe
  if (!curr_node %in% output_tree$node_number) {
    if (curr_node != 0){
    newval <- data.frame(node_number = curr_node, split_var = variable , split_value = value , parent = parent_node, leaf_log = leaf, y_val = est_val, criteria = det_criteria(curr_node, variable))
    output_tree <<- rbind(output_tree, newval)  
    }
  }
  
  #Creating a split on the current node
  split_val <- find_best_split(df)
  
  #Stopping criterion for determining terminal node 
  if (split_val[1] == 0 | curr_node >= 2**(max_depth-1) | nrow(df) < min_node_size) {
    est_val <- round(sum(df$voted)/nrow(df)) #majority vote for estimating predicted value at terminal node
    output_tree[output_tree$node_number == curr_node,]$leaf_log <<- TRUE
    output_tree[output_tree$node_number == curr_node,]$y_val <<- est_val
  }
  #Recursive call to create children nodes if stopping criterion not met
  else{
    branches <- create_split(df,split_val[2],split_val[3])
    left_branch <- build_tree(branches[[1]],1 + curr_node*2, curr_node, split_val[2], split_val[3])
    right_branch <- build_tree(branches[[2]], 2 + curr_node*2 , curr_node, split_val[2], split_val[3])
  }
}

Traversing a tree to predict outcome

tree_traverse <- function(df, tree = output_tree, curr_node = 0) {
  terminal <- FALSE
  #Running the loop until I reach terminal node
  while (terminal == FALSE) {
    var <- unique(tree[tree$parent == curr_node,]$split_var)
    check_val <- unique(tree[tree$parent == curr_node,]$split_val)
    if (var != 'age') {
      if (df[var] == check_val){
        curr_node <- 1 + curr_node*2    #If True or Yes, move to the left side child node
      }
      else{
        curr_node <- 2 + curr_node*2    #If False or No, move to the right side child node
      }  
    }
    else{
      if (df[var] < check_val){
        curr_node <- 1 + curr_node*2    #If less than, move to the left side child node
      }
      else{
        curr_node <- 2 + curr_node*2    #If more than, move to the right side child node
      }
    }
    terminal <- tree[tree$node_number == curr_node,]$leaf_log
  }
  est_y <- tree[tree$node_number == curr_node,]$y_val #If terminal node reached, determine the predicted outcome for the observation
  return(est_y)
}

#Function to create the prediction array based on input dataset
predict_tree_output <- function(df) {
  pred_y <- apply(df,1,tree_traverse)
  return(pred_y)
}

We create a deeper tree, and then prune it to check if pruning can help further

#Refreshing the dataset since the previous ones were added with prediction columns

test <- gotv[ind,]

deeper_tree <- rpart(voted ~ ., data = train, method = "class", control = list(maxdepth = 32), cp = -1)
pruned_deeper_tree <- prune(deeper_tree, cp = 0.001)

test$deeper_pred <- predict(deeper_tree, newdata = test, type = "class")
test$pruned_pred <- predict(pruned_deeper_tree, newdata = test, type = "class")
deeper_test_error <- check_err(test$deeper_pred, test$voted)
pruned_test_error <- check_err(test$pruned_pred, test$voted)

Pruning a deeper tree resulted a decrease of classification error from 0.2926872 in the initial tree to 0.2894622 in the pruned tree.

Part e - Interpretation of Result

  1. Pruning of the tree resulted in an increase of classification error since the original tree did not have enough depth (=6) to start with. Pruning a deeper tree leads to reduction in test error.
  2. Based on both trees created, the treatment variable doesn’t feature untill a depth of 6 - indicating that the treatment variable is not important. This argument is further strengthened by the fact that the rtree model ranks treatment as the second lowest important variable.

Part f - Creating a Random Forest

create_RF <- function(df, pred_var, n_pred, percent_obs, num_trees, complex_param, max_depth) {
  #n_pred: number of variables to be used for each weak learner
  #percent_obs: percetange of the training set used for each tree
  #num_trees: number of weak learners to create the forest
  #complex_param: compexity parameter for the rpart
  #max_depth: depth of the trees created
  rforest <- list()
  
  for(i in 1:num_trees) {
    
    # Sampling predictors for creating a tree
    sampled_preds <- sample(pred_var, n_pred, replace = FALSE)
    
    # Sampling observations for training tree
    in_bag <- apply(df, MARGIN = 1, FUN = function(v) ifelse(runif(n = 1, min = 0, max = 1) <= percent_obs, 1, 0))  
    temp_df <- cbind(df, in_bag)
    in_bag <- which(temp_df$in_bag == 1) # df rows which will be used to train the model
    
    # Building the tree
    t_control <- rpart.control(cp = complex_param, maxdepth = max_depth)   
    tree <- rpart(formula = temp_df[in_bag,"voted"] ~ ., data = temp_df[in_bag,sampled_preds], method = "class", control = t_control) 
    
    # add the tree to the forest
    rforest[[i]] <- tree
  }
  
  return(rforest)
}
#Refreshing the dataset since the previous ones were added with prediction columns
train <- gotv[-ind,]
test <- gotv[ind,]
coln <- colnames(train)[1:8]

n_weak_learners <- 25 #number of trees
rf <- create_RF(train, coln, 5, 0.8, n_weak_learners, -1, 6)
threshold <- n_weak_learners/2
#Defining a function to determine majority vote
majorityThres <- function(x) {
  if (x > threshold){
    return(1)
  }
  if (x < threshold){
    return(0)
  }
  if (x == threshold){
    return(rbinom(1,1,0.5)) #flipping a coin in case of a tie
  }
}
#Predicting outcome for each tree
pred_columns <- c()
pred_df <- data.frame()
for (i in 1:n_weak_learners){
  new_col <- paste("pred",i, sep="_")
  test[[new_col]] <- predict(rf[[i]], newdata = test, type = "class")
  pred_columns[i] <- new_col
}

#Converting factor-level predictions into numeric type
indx <- sapply(test, is.factor)
test[indx] <- lapply(test[indx], function(x) as.numeric(as.character(x)))
test$sum <- rowSums(test[pred_columns])

#Taking a majority vote across different tree predictions
new_val <- lapply(test$sum, majorityThres)
test$RFPred <- new_val
rforest_test_err <- check_err(test$RFPred, test$voted)
print(rforest_test_err)
## [1] 0.291663

The classification error based on the Random Forest (with 25 weak learners) is 0.291663 compared to the single tree with a test error of 0.2900288
